ladders.explanation:
The brute force approach to the celebrity problem systematically examines every possible candidate against all other people to verify the celebrity conditions. The intuition is straightforward: a celebrity is someone who is known by everyone but knows no one. By checking each person i against every other person j, we can validate both conditions: i must not know j (ensuring they know no one), and j must know i (ensuring they're known by everyone). This exhaustive verification guarantees we'll find the celebrity if one exists, or identify that there isn't one. The algorithm starts by considering each person as a potential celebrity candidate. For each candidate, we iterate through all other people to check two conditions: whether the candidate knows the other person (which would disqualify them) and whether the other person knows the candidate (which is required). If any check fails, we move to the next candidate. If we complete the inner loop without disqualification, we've found the celebrity. The time complexity is O(n²) because we have nested loops checking n candidates against n-1 other people each. Space complexity is O(1) since we only use a few variables. This connects directly to the key subroutine (L1) which is the candidate verification logic. Common mistakes include: 1) Not handling the case where no celebrity exists (must return -1), 2) Forgetting to check both conditions for each pair, 3) Off-by-one errors in loop indices, 4) Not optimizing the inner loop to break early when a disqualifying condition is found. The real code pattern involves nested loops with careful condition checking.

Pseudocode:
function findCelebrity(n, knows):
    for i from 0 to n-1:
        isCelebrity = true
        for j from 0 to n-1:
            if i != j:
                if knows(i, j) or not knows(j, i):
                    isCelebrity = false
                    break
        if isCelebrity:
            return i
    return -1

The candidate verification subroutine is the heart of the brute force approach. Given a candidate index i and total number of people n, this function checks whether person i could be the celebrity by verifying two conditions against every other person j: 1) i does not know j (celebrity knows no one), and 2) j knows i (everyone knows the celebrity). The intuition is that we can isolate the verification logic for a single candidate, making the main algorithm cleaner. This subroutine returns true only if all checks pass for all other people. The step-by-step algorithm: Initialize a flag isCelebrity to true. Loop through all people j from 0 to n-1. If j equals i, skip (a person always knows themselves in this problem's typical formulation, though we should check the actual knows(i,i) value based on problem definition; usually it's 1 or irrelevant). For each j ≠ i, check two conditions: if knows(i, j) is true, then i knows someone else → disqualify. If knows(j, i) is false, then someone doesn't know i → disqualify. If either condition fails, set isCelebrity to false and break early (optimization). After checking all j, return isCelebrity. Time complexity is O(n) for checking one candidate against n-1 others. Space complexity is O(1). This connects to the full problem (L0) as the inner verification logic that gets called for each candidate. Common mistakes: 1) Not skipping the self-check (i==j) properly, 2) Not breaking early when a disqualifying condition is found, 3) Misunderstanding the knows matrix semantics, 4) Not handling edge cases like n=1. The real code pattern is a simple loop with condition checks.

Pseudocode:
function isCelebrityCandidate(i, n, knows):
    for j from 0 to n-1:
        if i != j:
            if knows(i, j) == 1 or knows(j, i) == 0:
                return false
    return true

The core logic of the brute force approach is checking the celebrity conditions between any two people i and j. This is the fundamental operation that gets repeated in the verification subroutine. The intuition is simple: for i to be a celebrity candidate when compared to j, two conditions must hold: 1) i does not know j (celebrity knows no one), and 2) j knows i (everyone knows the celebrity). If either condition fails for any pair (i,j), then i cannot be the celebrity. This pairwise check is the building block that gets applied to all pairs in the verification process. The algorithm is straightforward: given indices i and j (with i≠j), check knows(i,j) and knows(j,i). Return true if knows(i,j) is false AND knows(j,i) is true. Otherwise return false. Time complexity is O(1) for a single check. Space complexity is O(1). This connects to the candidate verification (L1) as the atomic operation performed for each pair. Common mistakes: 1) Confusing the order of indices in the knows function, 2) Not handling the case where i=j (though typically skipped in the main algorithm), 3) Misunderstanding boolean logic for the conditions. The real code pattern is a simple conditional check.

Pseudocode:
function checkPair(i, j, knows):
    if knows(i, j) == 0 and knows(j, i) == 1:
        return true
    else:
        return false

Note: For celebrity verification, we actually need the opposite - we want to check if the pair DISQUALIFIES i. So in practice, we check if knows(i,j)==1 OR knows(j,i)==0, which would disqualify i.
